               <p>2d Count. Laying them to be the property of 
               <persName id="t17780429-91-person764">
                  Joseph
                   Williamson
               <interp inst="t17780429-91-person764" type="surname" value="Williamson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17780429-91-person764" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17780429-91-person764" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the elder, and 
               <persName id="t17780429-91-person765">
                  Joseph
                   Williamson
               <interp inst="t17780429-91-person765" type="surname" value="Williamson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17780429-91-person765" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17780429-91-person765" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the younger.</p>

               <p>(It appeared upon the evidence, that the hats were stolen out of the Luton Waggon in <placeName id="t17780429-91-crimeloc435">Gilt-Spur-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17780429-91-crimeloc435" type="placeName" value="Gilt-Spur-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17780429-91-crimeloc435" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17780429-91-off433 t17780429-91-crimeloc435"></join>. The prisoner afterwards sent two hats to the prosecutrix's as a sample of some hats he had to sell. A servant of her's, who manages her business, immediately knew them to be the hats which had been stolen out of the waggon. He made an excuse to leave the house, intending to fetch a constable; but when he returned with a constable, and searched the house, there was but one of the hats to be found, which was produced in court, and deposed to.)</p>

               <p>[The prisoner in his defence called 
